      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.fourpoundbrain.com/?p=176</guid>
      <description>Is your fish aquarium infested with algae, giving your tank an unpleasant appearance? Want to know how to get rid of algae in a fish tank? There are ways to get rid of this gross substance, which also will improve the quality of life for your fish. Read the tips below to learn ways to [...]&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/four-pound-brain/Four_Pound_Brain-How_to_Get_Rid_of_Algae_in_a_Fish_Tank.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Is your fish aquarium infested with algae, giving your tank an unpleasant appearance? Want to know how to get rid of algae in a fish tank? There are ways to get rid of this gross substance, which also will improve the quality of life for your fish. Read the tips below to learn ways to get rid of the algae and keep that aquarium clean in the future.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Do you have any friends or family that own an aquarium? Ask them about upkeep, and getting rid of the algae. What works best for them? Try that technique. If you still are having the problem, read below.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Know that there are different algae types that can grow in an aquarium, and be prepared to fight them off.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3:</strong> Lower your nutrient levels in the tank. This will get rid of any slime algae in the aquarium. Also change the water, and siphon away the slime.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4:</strong> Lower your light levels because that which is good for plant growth is also beneficial for growth of algae.</p>
<p><strong>Step 5:</strong> Keep sunlight away from the aquarium, because this too will help in algae growth.</p>
<p><strong>Step 6:</strong> Get some grazing snails because they will eat some kind of algae.  Also get a gentle scrubbing pad if you have an acrylic aquarium. You can scrub away the algae infesting your tank.</p>
<p><strong>Step 7:</strong> Get a razor blade to scrape tanks made of glass, but be careful not to scratch the glass.</p>
<p><strong>Step 8:</strong> Some fish eat algae, so purchase some of them. This is your best route to take as it is natural, and actually should be the first fish in your tank.</p>
<p><em>Tips</em></p>
<ul>
<li>Algae spores are found everywhere, and can also be inside your aquarium, even if new. Spores will tend to grow if there is plenty of light and nutrients- considered the right conditions.</li>
<li>Soak new plants in a solution of one part bleach to 20 parts water. Dip the plant in the solution for about two minutes and rinse. Dip the plant in water that is treated with a dechlorinator. This will neutralize remaining bleach before you add your plant to the tank.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Items Needed</em></p>
<ul>
<li>Fish aquarium</li>
<li>Water-bleach solution</li>
<li>Algae-eating fish</li>
<li>Grazing snails</li>
<li>Dark environment</li>
</ul>
]]></content:encoded>
